• **High revenue cost, weak targeting.** The Bipartisan Policy Center estimates the deduction will cost **$40 billion** through 2034; CRFB’s broader tip‑tax‑exemption model suggests behavioral shifts could push the loss toward **$150 ‑ $250 billion** as wages are re‑characterized as tips.  :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}  
• **Limited benefit to lowest earners.** About 37 % of tipped workers pay no federal income tax today; the deduction therefore delivers no gain to them, while higher‑earning servers and bartenders (or salon owners using booth‑rental models) enjoy the full break.  :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}  
• **Gaming risk.** The bill tasks Treasury with anti‑abuse rules but expressly allows deductions up to the highly‑comp threshold—creating strong incentives for restaurants to replace hourly wages with ‘mandatory tips’ or service‑charge distributions re‑labeled as voluntary cash.  Past experience with tip‑credit expansions shows under‑reporting and misclassification surge absent intensive IRS oversight.  :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}  
• **Administrative burden.** DMVs, gig platforms, salons, and payment processors must alter 6041/6050W reporting to flag tip amounts and occupation codes—complex IT changes that IRS and industry groups warn cannot be implemented before the 2025 filing season, risking mismatches and refund delays.
